One thing you have to understand is that when a assertion failed, the method is exited because an Error is thrown.  There is no way to avoid this unless you write your own JUnit app.  I don&#39;t think that it&#39;s what you want...

if you have 3 mendatory fields, you write 4 methods.  The first 3 test that you successfully see when fields are missing and the 4th to see if everything&#39;s fine when you have your 3 mendatory fields.  You have done quite the same thing (removing one field after another) but my approach is more simple.  

Remember: &quot;keep tests simple&quot;.  The more complicated the test code is, the more likely you introduce errors in the test code.  The goal of unit testing is not to debug your test code :-)

to implement the simpliest tests possible:

- use the setUp() method to create your data object
- create 4 tests methods (in my example it&#39;s 4)
- remove one single mendatory field at the beginning of each test method
- call the fail() method to tell JUnit that something wrong happend

private Data data;

public void setUp () {
  data = new Data();
  data.put(...);
}

public void testField1Missing () {
  data.remove(...);
  try {
     profile = home.create(data);
  } catch (IllegalFieldsFormatException e) {
     // if home throws this excpetion when a field is missing, it&#39;s fine
  }
}

public void testAllFieldsOK () {
  try {
     profile = home.create(data);
  } catch (IllegalFieldsFormatException e) {
     fail(&quot;this execption should not have been thrown&quot;)
  }
}

